item.description:
arXiv:2502.15211v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: Abridged. Stochastic fluctuations in the spin frequency $
u$ of a rotation-powered pulsar affect how accurately one measures the power-law braking index, $n_{m pl}$, defined through $\dot{
u}=K
u^{n_{m pl}}$, and can lead to measurements of anomalous braking indices, with $\vert n \vert = \vert 
u \ddot{
u}/ \dot{
u}^{2} \vert \gg1$, where the overdot symbolizes a derivative with respect to time. Previous studies show that the variance of the measured $n$ obeys the predictive, falsifiable formula $\langle n^{2} angle = n_{m pl}^{2}+\sigma^{2}_{\ddot{
u}}
u^{2}\gamma_{\ddot{
u}}^{-2}\dot{
u}^{-4}T_{m obs}^{-1}$ for $\dot{K}=0$, where $\sigma_{\ddot{
u}}$ is the timing noise amplitude, $\gamma_{\ddot{
u}}^{-1}$ is a stellar damping time-scale, and $T_{m obs}$ is the total observing time. Here we combine this formula with a hierarchical Bayesian scheme to infer the population-level distribution of $n_{m pl}$ for a pulsar population of size $M$. The scheme is validated using synthetic data. For a plausible test population with $M=100$ and injected $n_{m pl}$ values drawn from a population-level Gaussian with mean $\mu_{m pl}=4$ and standard deviation $\sigma_{m pl}=0.5$, intermediate between electromagnetic braking and mass quadrupole gravitational radiation reaction, the Bayesian scheme infers $\mu_{m pl}=3.89^{+0.24}_{-0.23}$ and $\sigma_{m pl}=0.43^{+0.21}_{-0.14}$. The $M=100$ per-pulsar posteriors for $n_{m pl}$ and $\sigma^{2}_{\ddot{
u}}\gamma_{\ddot{
u}}^{-2}$ contain $87\%$ and $69\%$, respectively, of the injected values within their $90\%$ credible intervals. Comparable accuracy is achieved for (i) population sizes spanning the range $50 \leq M \leq 300$, and (ii) wide priors satisfying $\mu_{m pl} \leq 10^{3}$ and $\sigma_{m pl} \leq 10^{2}$, which accommodate plausible spin-down mechanisms with $\dot{K}
eq0$.
